text: 22oz bottle thanks to toby. Pours out black topped with a tan head. Nose is nice coffee roast malts chocolate caramel sweetness. Taste is more of the nice roast malts chocolate sweetness pepper caramel and a kick of coffee.

Bottle shared by a friend. Pours darkest brown with a thick tan head. Nose of malt, green pepper, coffee and chocolate. Malty and chocolatey flavor with coffee accents before a slight green pepper finish.

Dark brown/black color; Medium to heavy slightly creamy body; Aroma of toasted malt, coffee/espresso, cocoa powder, & some hops; Flavor of roasted sweet malt, caramel, rich coffee/espresso, dark chocolate, and some hops; Nicely balanced; Tasty - pretty good.

Pours opaque chocolate brown with a decent light tan head. Aroma features peppery, coffee and roasted malt notes. Flavor offers coffee, some kind of fresh vegetable, and coffee tones plus a hint of molasses. Mouthfeel delivers good fizz and body. Split yer wig!

Bottle 22oz.
Pours dark brown with low to no head. Aroma is of roasted malt, chocolate. Taste is of roasted malt, chocolate. Palate: Full bodied, medium carbonation. Overall: Not much to see here.

Draught at 20th Pizza Port Strong Ale Festival. Pours opaque black with a medium, frothy tan head, medium retention with good lacing. Aroma is oats, rich coffee, prunes and figs with roast malt. Flavor is heavy roast malt, rich espresso, prunes and figs with creamy oats and a sweet finish. Full body and medium carbonation.

Style et résumé: Coffee stout. 
Comment: Dégustation Manseau Automne 2016, Merci Tommy et les autres.
Portrait:  Un liquide brun foncé. Un nez intense de chocolat et de café artificiel. Une bouche de chocolat, café, moyennement mince. Il y a une amertume qui accroche en finale.
Note:  6+/10
Black. Nose of chocolate and roast coffee. Flavor is sweet dark chocolate with roast, coffee, and light vanilla.

3oz sample that poured almost black with no head. aroma was deep roasted malts and plenty of coffee, hints of chocolate and coffee. flavor in itself was good and it was a full bodied beer with lots of coffee and chocolate hints but mostly coffee.
Bottle from the source roughly about a year old. Still great Ethiopian coffee flavor. Bakers chocolate and a little vinagar.Really well made and great bold flavors and great body that holds up.

On tap.
Pours black with moderate tan head.
Aromas of black coffee, nutty dark chocolate and dry roasted malts. 
Flavors of cold espresso, ash, dusty dark chocolate and lots of dry heavily roasted malts

Pours a medium black with a light brown head that leaves some lacing. Nose is of coffee, chocolate and no green pepper. Taste is of coffee and moderately sweet. Roasty and a little boozy. Body is medium-full and carbonation moderate. An OK almost imperial stout but not awe inspiring.
Bouteille 650ml, bottle share. Couleur noire opaque, mousse moka pâle. Arôme de café, cacao, malt torréfié. Goût de café, malt torréfié, cendré, poudreux. Carbonatation faible, corps moyen.
Bottle. Pours a black color with a small tan head. Has a roasted malty coffee aroma. Roasted malty coffee and chocolate flavor. Has a roasted malty coffee finish.

Opaque black pour with tan head. Aroma is nice good toffee coffee light roast. Taste is pretty bland bad roasty flavor acrid. Palate is light med bodied with light carbonation. Good nose, taste is rough.

bottle at toms epic tasting 2016. pours unclear very dark brown with a small light beige cap offering some retention and lacing. stale coffee grains, roasted chocolate, vegetal, minerals. moderate carbonation, light to medium body - oily; sweet coffee-spicy finish. staled/or overlyboiled coffee stout. o-k.

Bottle (22 oz), shared. Thanks to Dresden for this one! Dark brown with a small beige head leaving little lacing. Aroma is of coffee, vegetal notes, chocolate, earthy notes and caramel. Taste is vegetal with coffee, lactose, chocolate and mild coffee bitterness. Medium body. Medium carbonation. Coffee and vegetal finish. A bit harsh. Decent Sweet Stout.

Café en évidence dans cette proposition qui suinte le lactose ou lavoine. Belle présentation. Au goût, nous y retrouvons du café et des malts rôtis qui apportent une certaine dureté. Corps de moyenne densité avec texture mousseuse. Amertume terreuse qui nest pas arrondie. Not a fan.

Bouteille. Robe noire opaque avec de minces reflets noisettes. Léger col de mousse beige. Arômes de chocolat noir, eau minérale, mélasse, noisettes, herbes séchées. En bouche, chocolat noir, noisettes, malt rôti et presque brûlé, café moulu, gaufrettes. Texture légère et corps moyen.

2 ounces at tasting. Aroma: intense quality coffee, roasted malt, maybe light raisin. App: dark brown, minimal mocha head leaving good lacing even in this small small glass. Taste and palate: medium body, velvety, medium sweetness with moderate bitter finish. Overall: reminds me of some of Angry Chair beers by its sweetness. Its sweet but not too much, at least for this small pour. Well done.

On tap at Pazzos Pizza, Lexington, KY, 8.5.16. Black with a tan head. Lots of chocolate, porridge aroma. Dry, sweet with bitter undertones in the mouth, like good chocolate. Full body, long and creamy chocolate finish. Carbonated.

on tap @ Hebron Brewhaus / Hebron KY --- Aroma of sweet malt and earthy bran. Opaque black color, beige head that takes its time reducing to a cover, lace cobwebs. Taste is rich, chewy malt with toffee and an earthy, autumn leaf overtone that floats through medium carbonation to light hops, and then a lingering biscuit and honey finish. Alcohol warmth shows in the end. Complex and balanced, highest recommendations.

Bomber from the brewery, 5/6/16. Clear dark chestnut brown with a large foamy tan head. Good retention. Aroma of coffee, chocolate, oatmeal, roasted malt. The taste is roasted malts, coffee, coffee grounds, clay, oatmeal, cherries. Medium bodied, lingering roast. A bit harsh, but solid overall.

Glass, 1 pint, draught, on the premise, trip to Dark Lord Day with Philippe Boutin, Luc Bourbonnière and Ian Guénard, savoured on April 29 2016; eye: black, opaque, nice beige head, lots of lacing; nose: coffee, Coffee Crisp, roasted barley, light burnt barley, vanilla; mouth: coffee, Coffee Crisp, roasted barley, light burnt barley, vanilla, slight lactic, finale in Coffee Crisp, medium body, average carbonation, lightly sweet, slick texture; overall: quite good

FRANÇAIS

Verre, 1 pinte, en fût, bue sur place, voyage pour Dark Lord Day avec Philippe Boutin, Luc Bourbonnière et Ian Guénard, savourée le 29 avril 2016; il : noire, opaque, belle mousse beige, beaucoup de dentelle; nez : café, Coffee Crisp, orge torréfiée, léger orge brûlée, vanille; bouche : café, Coffee Crisp, orge torréfiée, léger orge brûlée, vanille, très léger lactique, finale en Coffee Crisp, corps moyen, carbonatation moyenne, légèrement sucrée, texture coulante; en résumé : très bon

Bottle shared at Travlrs departure tasting. Poured into a snifter showing pitch black with two quickly dissipating fingers of latte colored foam. 

The nose shows a mix of soy milk and adzuki. Strange but it works. 

The nose is moderately carbonated and light bodied. Lightly sweet with a light alcohol spiciness.Flavors of sweet milk chocolate and very faint roasted malts. Practically no bitterness.
Bottle at Travlrs DC Departure RateBeer Tasting. Thanks Iphonephan! Dark brownish black with tan head. Aromas of light coffee, roast. Tastes of dark chocolate, coffee. Medium body with a dry finish.
Lots of coffee and lots of roast. Black pour with decent head and lacing. Mocha head. Light sweet finish. Some milk. Bottle.
From a bottle at the RateBeer gathering 9/9/16. Ciffee aroma. Pours black with a tan head. Flavors of dark fruits. Smooth and delicisous,
Bottle. Clear ruby maroon color, thin tan edge head. Huge fruity coffee aroma. Taste is sweet coffe, bitter finish. Tasty for those who like coffee beers. Like me.

Bottle poured dark cola brown almost black with a thick tan head and nice lacing. Aromas of roasted chocolate malts, vanilla, cocoa, and lactose. Flavor is mild creamy cocoa bitter with a sweet milk chocolate finish. Yum.

Big thanks for this one, Matt! Sweet, lactic chocolate with just a hint of coffee on the nose. Slightly dilute for a big beer. Lots of flavor, definitely on the sweet side. Coffee is subdued. Good. Would be great with some oak.

UPDATED: AUG 28, 2016 Bottle in Seattle. Thanks again to Pruf. Nice thick tan foam, dense cold brew aroma. Sticky thick body, sweet creamy chocolate with thick espresso underneath. Some lactic note on the nose, but doesnt follow. Rich body, a bit more carb than I had expected. Solid coffee beer, quite sweet creamy underneath.
Pours a black color with a thin tan head. Roast coffee and malty aroma. An almost milk stout sweet start that finishes with light coffee and molasses.

Thanks to gregwilsonstl for sharing this one. It pours dark brown with a tan head. The aroma has coffee, another roasted malt and chocolate. It has a medium body with a light amount of carbonation. The taste starts with dry malt, coffee, dark caramel, toffee and a nice richness. Another winner here.

Oh yea, life is good. Dark black. medium mocha head. Smells like chocolate milk. Milky espresso goodness. Medium oily body. Chocolate lingers. I want this side by side with 4 Hands Chocolate Milk Stout. Thx again HankDaStank!

Bottle pour opaque black with huge tan head. Nose lots of coffee and espresso, some cherry and red fruit. Taste mostly coffee, some dark fruit and chocolate. Nice smoothness from the oatmeal. I like coffee so this is right up my alley.

Great flavor. Lots of coffee aroma and flavor. Good sweet malt and smooth mouthfeel from oats. Smooth drink and medium heavy mouth feel. A must try. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Belle texture soyeuse et crémeuse en bouche. Saveur de chocolat, despresso et dune légère fumée. Le tout se termine tres rondement en bouche et les saveurs disparaissent rapidement. Cette biere manque de longueur en bouche mais demeure très agréable à boire.

22. Thanks, C! Pours an opaque matte black with a dense and creamy burnt tan head that doesnt really stick around for too awfully long. Big coffee nose, kinda smells like 7-11 coffee, really--deep and earthy and fairly charred. Doesnt really smell like a great espresso, but still smells appetizing. Creamy medium body, satiny. Earthy, roasty mid palate, tons of coffee, a little black walnut. Not sweet. Its probably entered as a "Sweet Stout" cause theres oatmeal in it, but it drinks like an export stout, so it should really be listed as a dry stout. Since theres no export stout category. Yeah. Long dry finish.
Bottle shared by Kevin. Pours a dark dark brown with a layer of tan head. Aroma and taste of coffee, coffee, coffee, milk chocolate, and, roasted malts.

Bottle: The aroma consists of moderate chocolate, espresso, roast, faint burnt notes, and molasses. It pours a dark brown with no transparency and a large tan head that settles to a thin film outlined by a thicker ring. There is some soapy webbing left on the sides of the glass. The flavor starts with moderate dark chocolate and light molasses. The finish has moderate espresso, roast, mild anise, and hints of roasted grain. Its medium bodied with light-moderate carbonation.

Pitch pour with dark wet sand head, bubbles down to nothing but a faint ring. Floral coffee nose, chocolate, tad of American hops. Flavor is coffee, cola, floral and citrus hop presence, bright and weightless body. Bit of a sticky chocolate cola linger. Its ok.

Pours black with a mocha head that doesn’t leave mucha trace on the glass while dissiapting. Smell is malty with roasted malts, dark brad, banana bread, dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, moist soil and hints of alcohol. Taste is sweet, bitter and malty. Mouthfeel is soft, round and medium to full bodied. finish is sweet, bitter with roasted malts, dark bread, dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, mosit soil, leather and minerals. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a very dark brown with a very thin tan ring. Medium body with lost of lacing. Nice aroma of coffee. Very smooth coffee and oatmeal flavors. Not overpowering and has a very smooth finish. Not really my style but very enjoyable.

Bottle at home. Paired with Kill Bill vol 1 and IKEA furniture assembly. Deep dark pour, khaki head, good lacing. Big roasty coffee nose, tempered by milk chocolate. Tastes sweet like diner coffee with 3 packets of sugar and a healthy dose of cream. Roast comes through too, but definitely a sweet coffee stout. Medium body, texture between creamy and slick, average carbonation.
On tap at the 3 floyds brewpub. A black beer with a creamy tan head. Aroma is roasted with lots of coffee. Taste is also roasted, coffee, caramel. Very creamy, nice mouthfeel. Balanced. Great beer
Near black pour with tan head. Aroma smokey caramel and oats. Taste follows nose with sweet molasses. Very nice.

On tap at Lunar Brewing Co. and snifter served showing a black/brown hue, with a bit of ruby highlighting, a presentable layer of tan head foam, and web-like cling to the lacing. The nose was expressively roasted, dark espresso, cocoa, and some sweetness. Medium to full bodied, with decent carbonation, a bit of silkiness to the mouthfeel, and slightly syrupy texture. The taste added roasted and earthy bitterness, fairly hidden alcohol, with  dryness to the finish. An excellent sipper for java fans.

Pours pitch black with a creamy tan head. Aroma is heavy in coffee, with some roasted malts and toast. Taste is mildly sweet and quite dry, especially in the finish. Medium body, smooth on the palate, softer carbonation. Overall a fantastic stout.
Near black,let. Aroma is espresso light vanilla. Sweet cream, fresh roast coffee. Very good

This bottled brew from a bottle shop poured a medium sized head of foamy finely sized clear colored bubbles that were long lasting and left behind a very softly carbonated opaque except at the edges dark black brown colored body and a thick foamy lacing. The mild aroma was floral and coffee. The semi-thick mouth feel was tingly at the start and at the finish with a lingering coffee aftertaste. The yummy flavor contained notes of semi-sweet roasted malt mild hops burnt malt coffee and dark malt. Delicious and one I would certainly like to have again.

Bottle share on the 42nd as Three Floyds Wigsplitter. Many thanks to Matteo for this one. Very fresh bottling, elaborate label. Opaque black, big foamy dense brown head, light lacing. Aroma is charcoal, coffee, earth. Mostly strong coffee. Body is smooth with soft carbonation. Taste is strong coffee, coffee and milk powder, creamy instant coffee......coffee roast....strong coffee...strong coffee....cofi. A tasty beer, if a touch oversweet.

Draft: Poured a deep black color stout with a large light brown foamy head. Aroma of nice floral coffee notes with some light roasted malt notes. Taste is one of the best floral coffee notes with light bitter notes, some roasted malt and light lactose notes are also discernable. Boyd is smooth with nice creamy texture and great carbonation. Incredible well balance and very easy to drink  probably one of the best coffee stout I have tried in my life.
Bottle. Dark pour some head. Pepper(red), chocolate, roasted aromas. Flavors of coffee, roasted, sweet tones.
Thick coffee flavor to start. Not hoppy. Had at room temperature which brought out the coffee flavor even more. Very enjoyable

Taste:Smooth, semi sweet malty notes mixes with oats, vanilla. Creamy mouth-feel. Malty, coffee nose.
Black and opaque, with a tan delicate head of lace.
Slick, medium body.

As I drink a Three Floyds coffee stout in a bar in Shibuya I ponder the meaning of life and how Ive gotten to this point. Then I observe the beautiful coffee aroma and the delicious flavor and go on drinking this world class brew.
Bomber pours pitch black with nice tan, lacy head. Coffee, coffee, coffee aroma with rich dark chocolate chicory smooth finish. Overall, the benchmark for this style.

A deep dark stout with a thin lacing dark brown head. In aroma, loads of coffee essence, vanilla extract, mocha chocolate, alcohol warmth, beautiful. In mouth a nice coffee crisp chocolate bar, vanilla, Nutella, bourbon notes, intense and pleasing. On tap at brewery.

Bomber dated 2-18-16. Black with a thick mocha head that leaves nice lacing. Aroma is espresso beans, bakers chocolate, vanilla, oats, and cream. Taste is dark coffee, very dark chocolate, oatmeal, roasted malts, and some cream. Creamy overall with a semi dry finish. Outstanding.
On tap at Lone Wolf. Poured black brown with tan head. Aroma strong coffee and roasty choc. Light carb med bod. Taste rich dark choc loads of coffe some hop at the finish

Bottle shared at level 42 Canary wharf tasting. 5/4/2016. Many thanks to Matteo for this one. Pitch black coloured pour with a lasting loose mid tan head. Aroma is nice earthy spicy coffee, raw coffee bean, caramel. Flavour is composed of roast coffee, spicy raw coffee bean, caffeine, smooth roast. Palate is medium full bodied with a frothy smooth carbonation, slightly creamy.

5th April 201642nd Floor Tasting. Thanks to Matteo. Almost clear dark brown beer, thin tan head. Palate is light, semi dry and has modest fine carbonation. Trace of malt cream. Loads of fresh earthy coffee, like a cole espresso. Trace of malt sweetness. Light earthy coffee finish. Very coffee one dimensional but it a tasty number.
Bottle. Dark brown, near black, with a tan head. Coffee beans, espresso, chocolate, sweetness, and mild oatmeal. Nice coffee stout, strong coffee flavor, and smooth.

Tasted from bottle. Pours black with tan head. Lots of lacing. Aroma is fresh brewed coffee and a little chocolate. Taste is moderately bitter with flavors of coffee, pepper, chocolate, caramel. Nice coffee forward stout. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

UPDATED: APR 6, 2016 65cl bottle shared at the early April CW tasting, London. Acquired via trade, thanks to Ryan. It pours a dark brown color with a small beige head. Aroma is full-on big bold roasted coffee beans and espresso, light milk and vanilla, but mostly coffee. Taste is dry and medium sweet with loads of roasted coffee beans again, vanilla, milk chocolate and again loads of espresso. Medium bodied with good carbonation. Overall, awesome coffee profile

UPDATED: MAY 15, 2016 Bottle shared in London on the 42nd floor - many thanks to Matteo for this one. Pours deep brown-black with a thick, frothy khaki head. Strong earthy coffee in the nose, espresso, baking cocoa. Light to medium sweet flavor with robust coffee character, bitter scorched earth, hearty baking cocoa. Full bodied, lightly chewy, with fine carbonation. Earthy finish, lightly warming, with more dark espresso, charred wood. The coffee character is profound.

UPDATED: APR 6, 2016 Bottle thanks to MattyO. It pours black with a decent tan head. The aroma is bitter - sweet, dark chocolate, big coffee, earthy, rich treacle, rocky road, light spice, pepper and roasted malts. The taste is rich, roasted malt, dale chocolate, rocky road, big coffee action, earth, toast and light umami with a dry finish. Medium body and fine carbonation. Flavoursome and drinkable.

Bottle at the level 42 tasting V1.5 05/04/16, thanks to Matteo.
Light black topped with a decent tan swirl.
Nose is big coffee grinds, coffee cake, spice, earthy roast, black pepper.
Taste rich espresso, spice , earthy roast, cocoa powder, bitter roast.
Medium bodied, fine carbonation, semi drying close with an earthy roasted fanfare.
Solid cofffe lead stout.
user_location: Hazlemere, the lower Xhitlerns, Buckinghamshire, ENGLAND

text: Easily one of the best coffee stouts I have had. Coffee/espresso all damn day!

22oz bomber. Deep brown black body, looks unfiltered. Manages to be doughy and coffee forward at the same time. Doesnt come off with much malt depth for the ABV, maybe a little sugared up. Mellow and really clean either way. Not much hop bite at all, but really sweet specialty malt tones, almost cacao tone. Pretty excellent.
Nice dark beer with a bit of hops, but lots of bitter, bitter coffee. You do have to like coffee flavor as this is nicely roasted, but still pretty forward.
Bomber courtesy of Todd. Pours a black cola with a medium sized tan/light brown head. Aroma of coffee and cream, oatmeal, roasted malt and chocolate. Taste is much the same. Excellent.

Pours a deep, dark black, with minimal head. Aroma of roasted coffee, some chocolate. Flavor is quite bitter, with strong coffee presence. Theres a touch of sweetness, with some chocolate milk and a hint of dark fruit at work, too. Its pretty tasty.

6 oz. pour from Liquor Barn (Middletown Commons). Aroma: Moderate coffee that has a blueberry-like character; lighter semi-sweet chocolate. Appearance: Pitch black with a foamy tan head that settles into a sticky skin. Flavor: Blueberry coffee notes up front that carry little acidity; lighter chocolate thereafter; coffee notes become more roast-centric towards the finish, which is mostly dry. Palate: Medium body, sticky texture, soft carbonation, abrupt finish. Overall: The high quality of the coffee treatment here makes this a winner where other, similarly less balanced beers might stumble.

Black pour with a creamy and frothy beige head and lots of lacing ..... Aroma of lactose, vanilla, roasted malts, espresso and caramel malts .... Taste is of lactose sugar and reminds me of cafe latte right away, roasted malts, vanilla, coffee, creamy, sweet chocolate ... The lactose is countered perfectly by the roasted coffee flavor .... Finishes roasted and lightly bittered with butterscotch notes .... Soft, silky and slightly slick .... Delicious

Bottled 2/18/16 and drunk 3/5/16.Deep chocolate-mahogany body shows fair clarity and dark auburn-garnet highlights on the edges while a tan head tops it, with moderate retention.Not intensely dark and bitter is the coffee aspect, thankfully, with milk chocolate character probably coming from the base malts mixing in with the roasted ones. Whatever the case, theres a great balance between malt and coffee, with vanilla and light espresso, tending to more mild chocolate on the finish. No alcohol noted, low on fruitiness. No flaws.Coffee flavors are immediately wrapped about sweet, cocoa-vanilla tinged base malts tending quite milk chocolatey and roasty through the middle and ending slightly more bitter and bready, with strong coffee dryness and lingering roasted bean characteristics. No alcohol, again, and with ample carbonation showing moderate tightness to create a very supple texture. A bit on the sweet side, though nothing out-of-the-ordinary, but very well balanced in the coffee department.

Tasting at Hackneys Printers Row. The aroma is pure black coffee. Taste follows suit. Not much other than really good freshly roasted coffee layered over a well made sweet stout. But what else do you need? Well done.

22oz bomber thanks to Sheepdog on HBT. Pours black with a finger of creamy dark tan head. Aroma of rich coffee, creamy vanilla, milk chocolate, hints of earthiness. Taste mimics the nose. Mouthfeel is super creamy. Solid stuff and a much needed stress reliever at the moment.

January 16, 2016. Bottle, shared by rlgk.
Black with a small brown head. Aroma is malty, some toffee, licorice, chocolate, hints of alcohol and dark bread. 
Taste is medium sweet, light bitter. Finish is sweet malty, soft bitter and slight boozy with toffee, some licorice, chocolate, dark bread and earth. Medium to full bodied, soft carbonation.
A: Pitch black wuth a small head N: Hazelnut, coffee T: Hazelnut, coffee O: Quite easy going with great flavours!

Bottle at Happy New Beer in Sätila 160116. Black beer with a nice beige head. Malty caramel aroma, chocolate, licorice, biscuits notes, some figs and tobacco. Roasted chocolate flavor, caramel, dark bread, raisins, some licorice. Nice body. Good beer, balanced and not extreme in any way.

Bottle courtesy of rlgk. Pours black with a mocha head that doesnt leave mucha trace on the glass while dissiapting. Smell is malty with roasted malts, dark brad, banana bread, dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, moist soil and hints of alcohol. Taste is sweet, bitter and malty. Mouthfeel is soft, round and medium to full bodied. finish is sweet, bitter with roasted malts, dark bread, dark roast coffee, dark chocolate, mosit soil, leather and minerals. Solid malt-driven affair...

Bottle shared with Paul. Pours a deep blackish brown body with thin lace. Mouthfeel is medium to full-bodied with notes of espresso bean, rich coffee, bitter chocolate, oats and a soft bitterness towards the finish.
Bottle thanks to generous trader - pours dark brown tan head - nose/taste of espresso, toasted chocolate malt, toasted oats and vanilla cookie - medium body

22 ounce bottle, couldnt find the dating so I assume it was smudged off the bottle. Served in a nonic pint glass, the beer pours dark brown/black with about an inch and a half tan head that stayed around a while. Theres also a good amount of lacing. I like the aroma, the brew smells like coffee, burnt/charred malt, chocolate and vanilla. I think the taste is pretty much just like the aroma, theres lots of coffee, burnt/charred malt, bittersweet and milk chocolate, and vanilla flavors. Mouthfeel/body is medium, its creamy and a bit coating with a moderate amount of carbonation. Its also smooth and pretty easy to drink. I liked this brew a lot, definitely worth picking up if you like stouts and/or coffee beers! $11.99 a bomber.

Bottle. Pour is pitch black with a very small tan head. Aroma and flavor is huge espresso, light roasted coffee, and bitter coffee grounds. This is basically like drinking cold espresso with alcohol in it. Good.

Dark beer with a foamy brown head. Green roasted coffee bean nose. Coffee dominate flavor but with lots of supporting chocolate and vanilla flavors. Very smooth beer. Great balance of caramel sweetness and coffee bitterness. Like eating chocolate covered beans. Very nice coffee beer.

Refrigerated brown bomber, bottle October 2015, poured into a snifter. Black with medium beige head. Aroma is espresso, medium body, medium/low carbonation, and some small-bubble lacing. Taste is dark malt, espresso, roast, and some herbal hops. Worth the price?, not for me.

A fine stout from 3 Floyds. An aroma of coffee and malts. Pours to a nice jet black with a tight tan head. Laces the glass nicely. Has a smooth mouthfeel with a perfectly timed hint of coffee/espresso to finish.
The average person eats 8 spiders a year *eating 2nd bowl of spiders* "WHOS AVERAGE NOW DAD?"

Bottle, from b3shine (thanks Beau!), shared at game night. Very dark brown, creamy tan head. Rich chocolate and coffee aroma and flavour with a pleasant sweetness and toasty bitterness. Silky mouthfeel. Excellent!
user_location: the land of bitumen, beef & beer, Alberta, CANADA

text:
Bottle shared at the Beerhive 
Black with a tan head, some lacing. Aroma of coffee, roasted malts and some chocolate. Taste of dark roast coffee, sweet dark malts and rich chocolate 
Very nice and easy drinking.

Pours black with about two fingers of tan head. Aroma of coffee with cream... Milk chocolate, vanilla, hints of coffee. I love this nose in a beer, other beers I can think of in terms of aroma are Founders Porter and Southern Tier Choklat. Taste is cream, milk chocolate and a light, balanced coffee bitter finish. Very smooth, very drinkable. Body is light but incredibly balanced with soft carbonation.

The aroma is creamy espresso, chocolate, licorice, and fresh oat bread late. The beer is a dark, rich mahogany brown topped by a dense, creamy head that has good retention and good, dense lace. The taste is a medium high sweet and medium bitter. The slick beer has foamy carbonation and a medium body. The flavor profile includes rich lactose notes, coffee, caramel, and cream. It finishes smooth and clean with a slight spice, mild licorice, light nut note, and molasses with a late emergingin dark chocolate. The aftertaste is that of chocolate oatmeal cookies and milk.

Sample at GABF 09/26/2015, thanks to my sis for assistance with note-taking. Pours black with a medium tan head. Small patches of lacing. Coffee, malt and chocolate in the nose. Medium body with roasty malt and coffee flavors, with some malt in the background. The finish is roasted malt and mocha. Good bad all around.

Pours a really nice dark brown / black. Coffee colored head, dissipates quickly. Lots of vanilla in the nose with some great coffee / espresso. Not much carbonation. Espresso vanilla flavor is great for me. Borderline too sweet. Some peanut butter in there too. Like it, dont love it. Needs more to balance the sweetness.

Black pour with a single finger espresso colored head. Aroma is full of coffee. Mouth is chewy and syrupy. Taste is full of coffee and some chocolate. Sweet, but the bitter coffee creates some much needed balance. Very smooth and easy drinking. Lots of lace.
Pour from bottle shared with Dave and Travis on 9/19/2015. Really nice coffee aroma, not to big of a body, nice coffee and roast flavor.

Bottled July 22, 2015 enjoyed in an Indians tulip/snifter September 15, 2015. 

Look - Dark black body. Thick tan head with medium bubbles. Blotchy lacing is left behind. It looks very good. An aggressive pour was used to yield the thick head. 

Smell - The smell is typical hoppy bitterness for Floyds. Aside from this it is ice coffee. Chocolate.

Taste - Coffee and chocolate. There is vanilla too. 

Feel - Milky smooth. Doesnt feel too carbonated. Bitterness is left on the tongue. 

Overall - What oatmeal? This is very close to 50/50 coffee/beer. The looks is very tasty but not one for the non coffee lover.
Enjoyed in line at New Glarus. Dark black pour with a tan head. Coffee vanilla nose. Slightly sweet. Malty with some bitter chocolate finish. An excellent breakfast beer!
on tap at beermiscuous, dark brown color , niche of offwhite foam, creamy coffee and roast flavors , not bitter, good balance of roast notes, clean coffee finish

Bottle. Pours thick black with an off-white head that leaves behind sticky lacing. Smells of chocolate, dark roasted coffee, roasted malts. Tastes similar. Smooth and creamy with a light coffee bitterness that takes over mid palate. Average carbonation; lightly bitter finish.
22 ounce bottle. Thanks Al. Pours almost black with a nice tan head. Big coffee aroma. Taste is coffee, roasted malt, some chocolate, and more coffee. Nice coffee bomb.

Large shared bottle inn Atlanta. No sediment, 
Dark red brown body that is clear but nearly black in the glass. Somewhat weak head. 
Light to medium coffee in a fairly complex ale. This leaves the coffee nicely balanced with the stout. 
Slightly boozy. Lightly bitter. Smooth.

Bottle into a snifter. Huge coffee on the nose. Smells just like a cup of Joe. Big coffee taste with roasted malts and oats. A floyds floyds floyds homerun, indeed. Rivals founders breakfast stout IMO.

22 oz. bottle from DEPs, split with Ms. phaleslu. Pours a deep coffee brown color with a big tan head that settles into a ring and leaves sloppy lace in the glass. Aroma of espresso, chocolate, toasted and roasted malts, and sweet sugary brownies. Flavor of citrus, pine, pineapple, tobacco, earth, and espresso - surprisingly bitter and fruity based on the aroma. Light-medium bodied, with lower carbonation and a smooth mouthfeel. The hops hit the palate on the initial, with coffee in the finish. Thinner than anticipated. Very interesting coffee sweet stout.

On tap at Ei8ht Ball brewing in Cincy/Kentucky: black pour thin light tan head amber tint. aroma is roasty malt, chocolate, coffee. tastes are same. cocoa, vanilla, dark fruit. thinnish. little tinny. ok, didnt blow me away.

Bottle. Creamy coffee, chocolate, roasted barley malt, and hay aroma - excellent. Black with small head. Sweet chocolate, black coffee, malt, and moderately bitter herbal flavor. Decent body. Very nice.

Bottle shared by RussianDragon. Thanks man.

Near black body with a thick, beige cap. Grandiose coffee aroma. Freshly ground beans with lovely supporting aromas of roast and chocolate. Outstanding.

4oz on tap at Ei8ht Ball. Very dark brown, near black color. Thin ring of khaki head. A few bits of lace. Up front, whoa! Fantastic big coffee, but its not too bitter. Has some very nice maple syrup type character to it, as well as a bit of chocolate. Not as in-your-face coffee as the 3F Speed Ball (which I thought was great personally), but definitely a much better sweet malt balance. Moderate sweet taste, light to moderate bitter. Medium to bigger body, nice mild chewiness, though not thick. Mild slick finish. Pretty tasty coffee stout. I could probably do with more earthiness, and less sweetness, but thats just a matter of preference. I dig the big coffee though, and the maple nuance.

Draft. Deep brown/black body with a frothy tan head. Aroma of espresso coffee, roasted grain, dark chocolate. Hint of dark fruit, dates. The flavor is moderately sweet and lightly bitter. It finishes lightly to moderately sweet, lightly to moderately bitter and lightly acidic. Medium body, velvety texture, soft carbonation. Coffee tops the taste profile, but theres also chocolate, roast, fruit and a hint of pencil lead. Nonetheless, its balanced and smooth. Very nice beer.

On tap at 3 Floyds. Pours Black with a nice tan head and a treacle roma with a ton of coffee. There is a hearty dark molasses flavor that is overwhelmed by espresso. If you like strong coffee, this is a great brew.

Bomber. Black pour with one finger tan foam head that lingers. Chocolate, roast, and lots of coffee aroma. Taste is more of the same. Thinner feel than expected, just enough bitter. Another solid 3F stout. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

On draft at the GTMW15 pre-party. Aroma of huge espresso notes, mild chocolate and roast notes. Flavor is espresso, dominating. If you do not like coffee you will not like this stout. Deep and rich, strong coffee covers your palate. Some roast, chocolate, and earth notes. Lush body, above average carbonation. Lingering finish. This is nice.

Pour out of 22 oz bottle, dark black pour with tan head, aroma brought notes of dark cocoa, roast, coffee into a bit of espresso bean, some spice notes with more coffee, dark chocolate. Taste was a mix of dark fruit, coffee, espresso, fresh grounds into a bit of roast, dark chocolate, finishing fairly bitter, slight sweet. Nice vanilla as well as it warms. Very tasty.
Milk chocolate and espresso aroma. Taste is espresso grounds, milk chocolate, black licorice, cinnamon. As it warms some plum and vanilla notes added to the taste.
Great coffee smell, and wonderful color. Bitter beer with a bourbon note, that is not my palate but my dad LOVES it

Bottle:
Pours dark......just, almost, nearly black.....with a thick, brown, chunky head.
Milk chocolate, oatmeal, cold coffee aroma.
Taste is super-creamy, dark chocolate malt, cocoa, vanilla, bitter-sweet espresso....
Solid, rich, sweet...silky....like melted ice cream..
Dessert-level.....excellent and delicious.

Draft to taster. Looks good; a translucent brownish cola with foamy beige head. Smells do dark malt, dark chocolate, and coffee and roast. Tastes like it smells with a medium to medium full-bodied mouthfeel and more milky chocolate than solely dark on the tongue. Discernible espresso on the tongue as well. Enjoyable.

On draft. Opaque dark brown, tan head, good lacing. Smell is espresso and chocolate milk. Taste follows, very robust, toffee, burnt caramel, boozy raisin, above all strong coffee. Great balance of creamy and carbonation on the tongue. Damn fine.
22 ounce bottle. Pours dark with creamy tan head. Taste is espresso, chocolate, creamy goodness. Delicious.
Aroma of freshly ground coffee, with strong espresso flavor balanced by sweet chocolate. Nitro pour gives it a velvety smooth mouthfeel.

monster of an espresso stout done really well. pours like motor oil with an oily tan colored head. strong roasted malt flavors and an aroma of dark black coffee. very smooth. best in class and one of the best beers that has come out from FFF in a long time.

Pours thick black unclear coffee in color with a creamy bright caramel head. Huge coffee espresso notes so nice in the nose. Flavor is big coffee on a creamy body, so smooth and cold and delicious. Sweet more than roasted which my taste buds worship.
Big coffee bean aroma and taste. Raisin and chocolate flavours with expresso and hops. Fruity date and fig. Some lace lines in opaque chemistry.

Bomber courtesy of and shared with Kermis. Big thanks.
Thick creamy tan head. Clear black pour. Lovely coffee aroma and aftertaste. A lovely brew

Bottle shared. Pours near black with a beige head. Aroma of massive espresso, dark chocolate, toffee, fudge, caramel and light roast. Flavour is over moderate sweet and bitter. Over medium bodied with soft carbonation.

Pours a deep opaque blackish hue with dark cascading body, some brownish Tootsie Roll gliw, frothy darker brown head dies to a mellow film, laces small with a decent ringer. Aromas are copious espresso, earth, roast, toffee and caramel meet jabs of cocoa, nib and toasty life. Cold press coffee, rich espresso, vibrant. Initial is medium bodied, a bit fuller as dome sticky malts and caramel meet expressive coffee, roast, earth. Cold press and espresso, cocoa, faint jab of nib, earth, dark chocolate. Middle is full, toasty, espresso dominant. A bit creamy at times, silky and dark. Cocoa nibs, chocolate wafer cookies, touch of creamy espresso makes this airy, light and fluffy over the palate. Silky dark roast, earth. Lovely stuff as usual from Floyds coffee repertoire. Rich, troasty dark and semisweet finish lingers well. Some cocoa nib roast, firm espresso and cold press life holds the reigns. A touch of caramel, toffee and subtle smooth oatmeal but the coffee addition does the work here. High class stuff
Pours black with tan head. Aroma is tons of coffee. Dark roasty coffee flavor and lots of it going on. Nice milky rich body, little bit of oatmeal. Great Coffee stout.

Draft pour at Birreria in Eataly. Black with tan head. Rich cocoa and malty coffee aroma. Big bold aroma - fantastic. Vanilla cream and rich coffee taste. One of the stronger coffee flavor a in a coffee beer I've had. Super tasty

Bomber from the source - fresh 7/22/2015 date, which would be the date it was purchased, thanks ck1 & H for the golden birthday!! Shared by my other brother. Black pour with a brown head. Nose has green coffee, huge espresso, a touch of treacle, and then eventually chocolate comes in strongly. Taste is of espresso, then chocolate and some lactose show through. Even gets fudgy down through the glass. Medium to full bodied and super smooooth, with little alcohol presence. Finishes well blended between the bitterness of the coffee and the cocoa/chocolate lactosey sweetness. Leaning slightly bitter, but very well blended. This was excellent. Hopeful it is more mass produced. 15.7

At the restaurant, nice black pour with a finger thick head. Aroma of coffee, espresso, heavily roasted oats and even still more coffee. Tastes like, what else? Coffee. Nice thick, creamy texture. This was an awesome brew!

Draft. The aroma does this beer no justice. It is almost all coffee. But....fuck...the taste explodes (natural male variety) with chocolate, oats, coffee, toasted malts, vanilla, and deliciousness. Badass!
on tap @ brewpub. coffee nose, coffee taste. some sweetness, some bite. creamy.
Draft at brewery. Great coffee aroma. Medium roast. The taste doesnt live up to how good it smells. Taste is coffee and creamer. Not much beer to this one. More iced coffee
